Step 2: Add Docker Hub credentials in Jenkins

1. Dashboard → Manage Jenkins → Credentials → System → Global credentials → Add Credentials
2. Kind: Username with password
3. Username: your Docker Hub username (iamprajwal99)
4. Password: your Docker Hub password (or access token – recommended)
5. ID: Docker (exactly as in the Jenkinsfile)
6. Description: Docker Hub credentials
7. Click Create

---

Step 3: Create a new Pipeline job in Jenkins

1. Dashboard → New Item
2. Enter a name: Docker-pipeline (or any name)
3. Select Pipeline → OK
4. Under Pipeline section:
   · Definition: Pipeline script from SCM
   · SCM: Git
   · Repository URL: https://github.com/Prajwalgb99/Docker_push.git (or your local repo path)
   · Branches to build: */main
   · Script Path: Jenkinsfile
5. Click Save

---

Step 4: Run the pipeline

· Click Build Now
· Watch the console output – stages will execute in order:
  1. Build Java Application – compiles HelloWorld.java
  2. Run Java Program – prints Hello from Jenkins!
  3. Build Docker Image – creates image using Dockerfile
  4. Login to DockerHub – uses stored credentials
  5. Push Docker Image – pushes iamprajwal99/docker_image:latest

Successful output (as you already saw):

```
Login Succeeded
The push refers to repository [docker.io/iamprajwal99/docker_image]
...
Finished: SUCCESS
```

---

Step 5: Verify the image on Docker Hub

· Go to hub.docker.com
· Log in → Repositories → iamprajwal99/docker_image – you'll see the latest tag.

---

Quick exam notes for B2

Component Purpose
agent any Run on any available Jenkins agent
environment Define variables (IMAGE_NAME, credentials ID)
withCredentials Securely pass Docker Hub username/password
bat Execute Windows batch commands (javac, docker, etc.)
post { always } Run docker logout even if build fails

---

If you need to run B2 again (troubleshooting)

· Docker not recognized? → Ensure Docker Desktop is running and Jenkins has permission (add Jenkins user to docker-users group on Windows)
· Login fails? → Re‑enter credentials in Jenkins; use an access token (not password) if 2FA is enabled on Docker Hub
· Push fails? → Verify image name exactly matches your Docker Hub username/repo

Your B2 is already working. For the lab, just be ready to explain each stage. Good luck!
